Do we really need both of these response types?

I normally wouldn't be too worried about it, but given they're template specializations, they're going to duplicate a lot of code.  Have you looked at the binary size increases here at all?  Would it make sense to refactor the method for this to be something like.

enum class OutputEncodingType{
  Raw,
  Base64,
};

openFile(int fd, OutputEncodingType encode)

Pass that into the Base64FileBody class, and use that to branch line  64 of http_base64_file_body.hpp

That way, we have one "file" implementation in multiple modes?

Something to consider.

Can't this be simplified to

while(result.size() < 10000){
    result += "sample text";
}

?


Up to you, either is fine.

how about adding code as below. Some times we get handle that already moved certain amount. 
off_t currentPos = lseek(fd, 0, SEEK_CUR);
fileSize = fileHandle.size(ec)-currentPos;

> how about adding code as below. Some times we get handle that already moved certain amount. 

Why would that happen in a way that's not a bug?  I would expect any FDs we open in process to be at the right place.  Any FDs sent over dbus should be the same.

> off_t currentPos = lseek(fd, 0, SEEK_CUR);
> fileSize = fileHandle.size(ec)-currentPos;

At most we would do -2, right?  The encoded size from a chunk is going to be:

size % 3 = 0;  EncodedSize is correct;
size % 3 = 1; EncodedSize is 2 larger, because of missing trailing ==;
size % 3 = 2; EncodedSize is 1 larger, because of missing trailing =;


While it's not technically correct (we might alloc 2 more characters than needed), I'm ok with it for the moment, especially given that this is reused between buffers, it seems very unlikely that we'd see a problem in practice.


I realize that I commented this on a previous patchset, but decided it wasn't worth the effort to make technically correct.
